# Peter's denial as the fulfillment of the passion's scatter-sheep pattern
FILL_CH14 = {
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>The Passover plot — two days before the festival, the chief priests and teachers of the law are seeking to arrest Jesus secretly and kill him. The Passover context is not background color; it is the interpretive frame: Jesus is about to become the Passover lamb, whose blood protects from judgment and whose death inaugurates the exodus from sin. The authorities plot in ignorance of their own role in divine redemption.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&#8220;But not during the festival, or the people may riot&#8221; — the irony: the authorities&#8217; plan to avoid the Passover crowd is precisely overridden by the divine timetable. Jesus dies at Passover, not despite the leaders&#8217; plans but through them. God&#8217;s sovereign purpose works through human resistance and scheming without removing the conspirators&#8217; moral responsibility.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The anointing at Bethany — a woman pours an entire jar of expensive pure nard on Jesus&#8217;s head. Anointing the head is the act of royal and priestly consecration (1 Sam 10:1; Exod 29:7); Jesus is anointed as king and priest on the eve of the passion. The extravagance of the act (a year&#8217;s wages poured out in a moment) mirrors the extravagance of the redemption it foreshadows.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;Some of those present were saying indignantly to one another, &#8216;Why this waste of perfume?&#8217;&#8221; — the protest is economically rational but theologically blind. They calculate the value of the nard without calculating the value of the one anointed. The &#8220;waste&#8221; language anticipates the cross: the death of the Son of God looks like waste to those who cannot see its redemptive purpose.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;It could have been sold for more than a year&#8217;s wages and the money given to the poor&#8221; — the objection is not wrong in its arithmetic but wrong in its theology. The anointing of Christ is not in competition with care for the poor; it is the act that makes possible the ultimate care for the poor by addressing the poverty of sin and judgment that money cannot relieve.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;Leave her alone. She has done a beautiful thing to me&#8221; — Jesus&#8217;s defense of the woman is a Christological statement: this act is beautiful because its object is Christ. The beauty of the anointing is not in its technique or cost but in the person it honors. What seems wasteful is revealed as worship; what appears excessive is recognized as appropriate to the one who is about to give his life.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;The poor you will always have with you, and you can help them whenever you want. But you will not always have me&#8221; — the unique moment of the incarnation demands a unique response. The window for anointing the incarnate Son before his death is brief; caring for the poor is a permanent and ongoing calling. Jesus does not diminish the obligation to the poor but names the singular irrepeatable moment that the woman has recognized.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;She did what she could. She poured perfume on my body beforehand to prepare for my burial&#8221; — Jesus interprets the anointing as preparation for burial. The woman may not have understood the full significance of her act, but Jesus names it as prophetically anticipating his death. The body anointed here is the same body that will die and be raised; the anointing is the first act of the burial sequence.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;Truly I tell you, wherever the gospel is preached throughout the world, what she has done will also be told, in memory of her&#8221; — the gospel and the anointing are permanently linked. Wherever the death of Christ is proclaimed, this woman&#8217;s act of costly devotion is proclaimed with it. Her namelessness in Mark does not diminish her honor; the memorial is permanent and universal. She is the model of what it means to recognize the value of Christ.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Judas goes to the chief priests to betray Jesus — the contrast with the anointing is sharp and deliberate: the woman gives extravagantly; Judas sells. The woman&#8217;s costly devotion (v.3-9) is immediately followed by Judas&#8217;s calculated betrayal. Both acts will be told &#8220;wherever the gospel is preached&#8221; — one as an example, the other as a warning.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;They were delighted to hear this and promised to give him money&#8221; — Judas&#8217;s betrayal is framed by money as the anointing was framed by extravagant gift. The &#8220;promise of money&#8221; echoes Zechariah 11:12 (thirty pieces of silver, quoted explicitly in Matthew); the betrayal for payment fulfills the prophetic pattern of the rejected shepherd. Judas becomes the instrument of the divine plan while choosing freely against his master.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The preparation of the Passover — the disciples ask &#8220;Where do you want us to go and make preparations for you to eat the Passover?&#8221; The Passover is the meal of liberation and covenant; Jesus is about to transform it into the covenant meal of his own blood. The disciples prepare the Passover meal; they do not yet know that they are preparing the context for the new exodus.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Jesus sends two disciples ahead with precise instructions about a man carrying a jar of water — the detailed foreknowledge (a man with a jar of water would be unusual; water-carrying was typically women&#8217;s work) demonstrates Jesus&#8217;s omniscience. He knows the city, the house, the owner&#8217;s willingness. The provision of the upper room is not accident but preparation; the Son of God directs the final hours of his own earthly ministry.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;The Teacher asks: Where is my guest room, where I may eat the Passover with my disciples?&#8221; — Jesus identifies himself as &#8220;the Teacher&#8221; and claims hospitality for the Passover meal. The &#8220;guest room&#8221; (<em>katalyma</em>, the same word used for the inn in Luke 2:7) is claimed by the one for whom there was no room at his birth. The last meal before the cross mirrors the first night of the incarnation: both times, a room is sought.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A large room upstairs, furnished and ready — the room provided is already prepared; nothing is left to chance. The &#8220;readiness&#8221; of the room (all that remains is for Jesus and the disciples to arrive) is the divine preparation: the Son of God moves toward the cross through a series of providentially prepared spaces and moments.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;The disciples left, went into the city and found things just as Jesus had told them&#8221; — the fulfillment of Jesus&#8217;s words continues the pattern of his omniscient control of events. The disciples have not yet grasped that this dinner is different from all others; they follow instructions and find what he said. Their obedient action is the vehicle of divine provision.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;When evening came, Jesus arrived with the Twelve&#8221; — the evening of Passover is the threshold of the new day by Jewish reckoning. Jesus arrives with the full Twelve including his betrayer; even in this final meal, the community of twelve is intact. The number twelve maintains its symbolic significance — the new Israel gathers for the last supper before the passion that will reconstitute it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&#8220;Truly I tell you, one of you will betray me — one who is eating with me&#8221; — the betrayal announcement at table is the gravest possible violation of covenant hospitality. To share a meal was to be at peace (Ps 41:9 — &#8220;even my close friend, whom I trusted, he who shared my bread, has turned against me&#8221;). Jesus names the betrayal without naming the betrayer, extending Judas a final moment of possible repentance and preserving the community&#8217;s testing of itself.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;They were saddened, and one by one they said to him, &#8216;Surely you don&#8217;t mean me?&#8217;&#8221; — the Greek <em>mēti egō</em> expects a negative answer (&#8220;It&#8217;s not me, is it?&#8221;). Each disciple examines himself rather than pointing at others; their genuine uncertainty about their own potential for failure is morally honest and theologically significant. The disciples do not know themselves; this is the same self-ignorance that will manifest in their flight and Peter&#8217;s denial.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;It is one of the Twelve, one who dips bread into the bowl with me&#8221; — Jesus narrows the circle to the shared bowl without naming the individual. The shared bowl represents the intimacy of the meal; the one who shares it is the one who will break it. Judas is given maximum opportunity to turn back; the dipping continues while the betrayal is still a choice.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;The Son of Man will go just as it is written about him. But woe to that man who betrays the Son of Man!&#8221; — the paradox of divine sovereignty and human responsibility is held without resolution: the passion is &#8220;written&#8221; (prophetically determined, Isa 53; Ps 22); Judas&#8217;s betrayal is freely chosen and morally culpable. The &#8220;woe&#8221; is not fate but judgment: it would be better not to have been born than to be the instrument of rejection that willingly chooses against the Son of God.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;Then he took a cup, and when he had given thanks, he gave it to them, and they all drank from it&#8221; — the cup of the Passover Seder carries the wine of the covenant; Jesus takes the cup and gives thanks (<em>eucharistēsas</em>) before reinterpreting it. &#8220;They all drank from it&#8221; — including the one who will betray him; the cup of the new covenant is offered to all, even to those who will not receive its benefits by faith.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;This is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many&#8221; — the covenant-blood language is layered: it echoes Exodus 24:8 (Moses sprinkled covenant blood at Sinai — &#8220;This is the blood of the covenant&#8221;) and Isaiah 53:12 (&#8220;he poured out his life unto death and bore the sin of many&#8221;). Jesus&#8217;s death is simultaneously the new Sinai (establishing the new covenant) and the fulfillment of the Servant&#8217;s substitutionary self-giving.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;Truly I tell you, I will not drink again from the fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new in the kingdom of God&#8221; — the eschatological vow points beyond the passion to the consummation. The Last Supper looks forward to the messianic banquet of the kingdom (Isa 25:6-8); the crucifixion is the death that makes the resurrection feast possible. The table fellowship broken by the passion will be restored and perfected in the kingdom.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;When they had sung a hymn, they went out to the Mount of Olives&#8221; — the Passover Seder concluded with the Hallel psalms (Ps 113-118), which include the great declaration of divine steadfast love over death. Jesus and the disciples sing of the rejected stone becoming the cornerstone (Ps 118:22) and &#8220;Save us, we pray, O LORD&#8221; (Ps 118:25 — the Hosanna) on the night before the cross. The hymn they sing is about him.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;You will all fall away, for it is written: &#8216;I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered&#8217;&#8221; — Zechariah 13:7, quoted as fulfilled in the passion events. Jesus is the shepherd who is struck; the disciples&#8217; scatter is not a personal failure only but a prophetically anticipated consequence of the passion. The fulfillment of Zechariah confirms that the passion is not a defeat but a divine plan carried out according to the Scriptures.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;But after I have risen, I will go ahead of you into Galilee&#8221; — even in announcing the scatter, Jesus announces the regathering. The resurrection will precede the disciples to Galilee; the scattered sheep will be led back by the risen shepherd. The promise embedded in the prediction of failure is the ground of resurrection hope; the disciples&#8217; flight is not the final word.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Peter: &#8220;Even if all fall away, I will not&#8221; — Peter&#8217;s self-confidence is the mirror image of the disciples&#8217; uncertainty in v.19 (&#8220;Surely not me?&#8221;). Where they honestly examined themselves, Peter asserts his own superiority to failure. The denial that follows is not merely a moral failure but the specific consequence of trusting one&#8217;s own resolve rather than acknowledging dependence on Christ.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;Today — yes, tonight — before the rooster crows twice you yourself will disown me three times&#8221; — the precision of Jesus&#8217;s prediction (tonight, twice, three times) is a Christological demonstration: he knows Peter&#8217;s heart better than Peter knows it himself. The foreknowledge does not remove Peter&#8217;s responsibility but surrounds it with the patient love of the one who knows and still calls him.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;But Peter insisted emphatically, &#8216;Even if I have to die with you, I will never disown you&#8217;&#8221; — the emphatic declaration (<em>ekperissōs</em>, exceedingly, beyond measure) intensifies the fall that follows. The disciples&#8217; collective &#8220;And all the others said the same&#8221; spreads the failure to the whole group; the Twelve collectively overestimate their own faithfulness. Gethsemane will prove them wrong.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;They went to a place called Gethsemane, and Jesus said to his disciples, &#8216;Sit here while I pray&#8217;&#8221; — Gethsemane (&#8220;oil press&#8221;) is where the weight of the cross begins to be felt. Jesus separates from the main group to pray; he takes the inner three with him (as at the Transfiguration). The movement from the supper table to the garden mirrors the movement in Eden: both involve a garden, a decision, and the consequences of relationship with God.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&#8220;He began to be deeply distressed and troubled&#8221; — <em>ekthambeisthai</em> (deeply distressed, horrified) and <em>adēmonein</em> (troubled, anguished) are among the strongest emotional terms in Greek. The incarnate Son of God, facing the cup of divine wrath, experiences genuine anguish. This is not performance or weakness; it is the authentic response of the holy one who is about to absorb what sin deserves. The genuineness of Gethsemane is the measure of the cost of the atonement.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;My soul is overwhelmed with sorrow to the point of death&#8221; — the language echoes Psalm 42:5 and 43:5 (&#8220;Why, my soul, are you downcast?&#8221;) and Jonah 4:9. Jesus prays with the Psalms on his lips; the passion is not only historical event but the fulfillment of the righteous sufferer&#8217;s lament. &#8220;To the point of death&#8221; may mean sorrow so intense it could kill, or it may point to the death that is the actual content of his anguish.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;Going a little farther, he fell to the ground and prayed that if possible the hour might pass from him&#8221; — falling prostrate is the posture of absolute surrender before God (Gen 17:3; Num 16:22). The &#8220;if possible&#8221; is not doubt about God&#8217;s power but honest human petition; Jesus brings his genuine desire to the Father rather than suppressing it. The prayer of Gethsemane is the model of honest petition submitted to divine will.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&#8220;Abba, Father, everything is possible for you. Take this cup from me. Yet not what I will, but what you will&#8221; — the most intimate prayer in the Gospels. &#8220;Abba&#8221; (Aramaic for &#8220;father,&#8221; conveying intimate address) is the address Jesus uses that the Spirit enables Christians to use (Rom 8:15; Gal 4:6). &#8220;Everything is possible for you&#8221; affirms divine omnipotence; &#8220;take this cup&#8221; is the honest petition of the one who knows what the cup contains; &#8220;not what I will, but what you will&#8221; is the eternal submission of the Son to the Father — the same submission that will be enacted on the cross.</p>",
    "37": "<p>&#8220;Simon, are you asleep? Couldn&#8217;t you keep watch for one hour?&#8221; — Jesus addresses Peter by his old name Simon, not the rock-name Peter; the use of Simon signals the pre-discipleship identity that Peter is reverting to. The failure to watch contrasts with the command of 13:37 (&#8220;watch!&#8221;) and with Peter&#8217;s emphatic promise of v.31. One hour of watchful prayer is the least form of cross-bearing; Peter cannot manage even this.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&#8220;Watch and pray so that you will not fall into temptation. The spirit is willing, but the flesh is weak&#8221; — the famous diagnosis of the disciples&#8217; failure applies to all who follow Jesus. The &#8220;willing spirit&#8221; is the genuine desire for faithfulness; the &#8220;weak flesh&#8221; is the human limitation that makes prayerful dependence on God essential. Self-confidence (Peter&#8217;s boast) bypasses prayer; watchful prayer is the channel through which the willing spirit overcomes the weak flesh.</p>",
    "39": "<p>He went away again and prayed the same thing — the repetition of Gethsemane prayer is itself a Christological statement: Jesus does not receive an immediate answer. He prays, returns to find sleeping disciples, and prays again. The Son of God experiences the delay of answered prayer that his disciples will also know; his perseverance in prayer is the model for the church&#8217;s perseverance in dark nights.</p>",
    "40": "<p>&#8220;When he came back, he again found them sleeping, because their eyes were heavy. They did not know what to say to him&#8221; — the silence of the disciples before Jesus is the silence of those who have nothing to offer in response to the one who is about to give everything. Their sleep is not simply exhaustion but the failure of solidarity; Jesus faces the cup alone.</p>",
    "41": "<p>&#8220;Are you still sleeping and resting? Enough! The hour has come. Look, the Son of Man is delivered into the hands of sinners&#8221; — the &#8220;hour&#8221; is the Johannine term for the passion (John 12:23; 13:1; 17:1); Mark uses it here at the decisive moment. &#8220;Delivered&#8221; (<em>paradidōmi</em>) is again the divine passive: the Son of Man is handed over by God to accomplish redemption. The Gethsemane prayer has been answered — not by removal of the cup but by resolution to drink it.</p>",
    "42": "<p>&#8220;Rise! Let us go! Here comes my betrayer!&#8221; — Jesus&#8217;s command to rise (<em>egeiresthe</em>) is the same resurrection word used in healings and will be used at the empty tomb. He rises to meet the betrayer actively rather than waiting; the cross is not something that happens to Jesus but something he walks into with sovereign freedom. &#8220;Let us go&#8221; — he leads rather than flees.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Judas arrived with an armed crowd from the chief priests, teachers of the law, and elders — the full Sanhedrin authority is represented in the arrest party. The irony of an armed crowd to arrest the one who had been publicly teaching in the temple (v.49) exposes the guilt they feel: force is necessary because they know they have no legitimate case. The weapons of the world come against the one who heals with touch.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The kiss as signal — Judas had arranged to identify Jesus with a kiss, the greeting of affection and loyalty. The betrayal uses the form of love; it is this inversion that makes it so deeply wrong. Jesus addresses Judas as &#8220;friend&#8221; (Matt 26:50) even in the moment of betrayal; the one betrayed maintains the posture of the one who loves.</p>",
    "45": "<p>&#8220;Going at once to Jesus, Judas said, &#8216;Rabbi!&#8217; and kissed him&#8221; — the term &#8220;Rabbi&#8221; (teacher) is Judas&#8217;s address to Jesus throughout (cf. v.45; in Matt 26:25 Judas alone uses &#8220;Rabbi&#8221; while the others say &#8220;Lord&#8221;). The form of respect masks the betrayal; the outward act of honor becomes the instrument of arrest. The kiss that marks for death is the specific form of the world&#8217;s rejection of the one it calls &#8220;teacher&#8221; without submitting to him as Lord.</p>",
    "46": "<p>&#8220;The men seized Jesus and arrested him&#8221; — the Son of God who commanded the wind and sea, who drove out demons, who raised the dead, is seized by human hands and arrested. He does not resist (cf. John 18:6, where the crowd falls back when he says &#8220;I am&#8221;); the sovereignty of the incarnate Son is expressed precisely in his willingness to be bound. The one who binds the strong man (3:27) allows himself to be bound for the world&#8217;s liberation.</p>",
    "47": "<p>One of those with Jesus struck the servant of the high priest and cut off his ear — Mark does not identify the attacker (John 18:10 names him as Peter). The sword-resistance is the disciples&#8217; last attempt to prevent the passion by force; Jesus rejects it (Luke 22:51 has him heal the ear). The kingdom does not come by the sword of disciples but by the cross of the King.</p>",
    "48": "<p>&#8220;Am I leading a rebellion, that you have come out with swords and clubs to capture me?&#8221; — Jesus&#8217;s question exposes the incongruity: the one who was daily in the temple, accessible and unarmed, does not require a military operation for arrest. The swords and clubs reveal the authorities&#8217; bad conscience; they arrest Jesus as a revolutionary because they know the real charge (blasphemy, v.64) requires their own initiative, not his.</p>",
    "49": "<p>&#8220;Every day I was with you, teaching in the temple courts, and you did not arrest me. But the Scriptures must be fulfilled&#8221; — the contrast between public teaching (accessible, open) and clandestine arrest (at night, with weapons) exposes the illegitimacy of the proceedings. &#8220;But the Scriptures must be fulfilled&#8221; — the passive of divine necessity (<em>dei</em>) frames the entire arrest as the unfolding of prophetic Scripture, not the triumph of human conspiracy.</p>",
    "50": "<p>&#8220;Then everyone deserted him and fled&#8221; — the fulfillment of 14:27 (&#8220;you will all fall away&#8221;) and Zechariah 13:7 (&#8220;the sheep will be scattered&#8221;). The disciples&#8217; unanimous desertion leaves Jesus facing the passion alone; the Son of God who was &#8220;always with&#8221; the disciples (v.49) is left without them. He bears the cross not only as their substitute but as their abandoned head — alone so that they will never finally be alone.</p>",
    "51": "<p>The young man following Jesus — a detail unique to Mark, possibly autobiographical (Mark himself?). The young man is following Jesus when everyone else has fled; his flight when seized is the final image of the disciples&#8217; desertion. The linen garment he leaves behind may echo the linen grave cloth that will be left in the tomb (15:46; 16:5) — even the image of abandonment anticipates the resurrection.</p>",
    "52": "<p>He fled naked, leaving his garment behind — nakedness is the condition of shame and vulnerability (Gen 3:7-10). The fleeing naked young man images the complete stripping of all cover that the passion requires: Jesus will be stripped of his garments at the crucifixion. The shame that disciples flee from is the shame that Jesus absorbs at the cross.</p>",
    "53": "<p>They took Jesus to the high priest, and all the Sanhedrin assembled — the full Sanhedrin (chief priests, elders, teachers of the law) assembles at night, which violates the procedural requirements of the Mishnah (capital trials were required to be conducted in daylight). The irregular proceeding exposes the assembly&#8217;s determination to achieve a predetermined verdict; the appearance of legal process masks a judicial murder.</p>",
    "54": "<p>Peter followed at a distance, right into the courtyard of the high priest — Peter&#8217;s following &#8220;at a distance&#8221; is the geographically appropriate image of failed discipleship: close enough to see, far enough to be safe. He sits with the guards, warming himself; the warmth of the fire is the warmth of belonging to the wrong side. The courtyard scene (Peter&#8217;s denial) will intercut with the trial above (Jesus&#8217;s confession) in verses 53-72.</p>",
    "55": "<p>&#8220;The chief priests and the whole Sanhedrin were looking for evidence against Jesus so that they could put him to death&#8221; — the goal is established before the evidence is sought; this is not inquiry but condemnation in search of justification. The Sanhedrin is not evaluating Jesus&#8217;s claim; they have already decided to kill him. The trial is a parody of justice that will ironically become the moment of Jesus&#8217;s most explicit self-disclosure.</p>",
    "56": "<p>&#8220;Many testified falsely against him, but their statements did not agree&#8221; — the requirement of two witnesses whose testimony agrees (Deut 17:6; 19:15) cannot be met even with false witnesses. The one who is the Truth cannot be convicted by lies that contradict each other; the failure of false testimony inadvertently confirms the innocence of the accused. God&#8217;s law, intended to protect the innocent, fails even in its violation to condemn the holy one.</p>",
    "57": "<p>Some gave this false testimony — standing up to testify falsely is an act of deliberate covenant violation (Exod 20:16 — &#8220;You shall not give false testimony&#8221;). Those who testify against Jesus at his trial become, in their very act of false witness, exhibits of the sin he is dying to atone for.</p>",
    "58": "<p>&#8220;We heard him say, &#8216;I will destroy this temple made with human hands and in three days will build another, not made by human hands&#8217;&#8221; — a distortion of Jesus&#8217;s temple-saying (John 2:19 — &#8220;Destroy this temple, and I will raise it again in three days&#8221;; John 2:21 interprets it as the resurrection of his body). The three days of the false testimony are accidentally the true timeline; the body destroyed at the cross is raised in three days. Even the false witness proclaims the resurrection.</p>",
    "59": "<p>&#8220;Yet even then their testimony did not agree&#8221; — the judicial deadlock caused by contradictory testimony forces the high priest to change tactics. The failure of external accusation leads to the direct question that will produce the decisive Christological disclosure. The passion narrative moves inexorably toward the moment when Jesus will speak the truth that seals his death.</p>",
    "60": "<p>The high priest asks: &#8220;Are you not going to answer? What is this testimony that these men are bringing against you?&#8221; — the question is an attempt to elicit self-incriminating testimony to cover the failure of the false witnesses. The high priest&#8217;s frustration is the frustration of power that cannot compel the testimony it needs from the one who holds all truth.</p>",
    "61": "<p>&#8220;But Jesus remained silent and gave no answer&#8221; — the silence of Jesus before the Sanhedrin fulfills Isaiah 53:7: &#8220;He was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth; he was led like a lamb to the slaughter, and as a sheep before its shearers is silent, so he did not open his mouth.&#8221; The silence is not passivity but the fulfillment of the Servant&#8217;s prophetic pattern. Only to the direct question of identity does he break it.</p>",
    "63": "<p>The high priest tore his clothes — the tearing of garments at a blasphemy accusation was a prescribed mourning act (m.Sanhedrin 7:5); the high priest performs the ritual that acknowledges he has heard blasphemy. The irony is that the one making the true claim (Son of God, Son of Man) is condemned for blasphemy, while those who condemn him for telling the truth are the ones who actually blaspheme.</p>",
    "64": "<p>&#8220;You have heard the blasphemy. What do you think?&#8221; They all condemned him as worthy of death — the Sanhedrin&#8217;s verdict on the true Son of God is &#8220;worthy of death.&#8221; The verdict is the climax of Mark&#8217;s trial narrative: the authorities have now formally rejected the one who is the Messiah and Son of God. The condemnation of the innocent one is simultaneously the judicial murder of the Son of God and the act by which the Son of God accomplishes redemption.</p>",
    "65": "<p>They spat on him, blindfolded him, struck him with their fists, and said &#8220;Prophesy!&#8221; — the mockery of the blindfolded prophet is hideously ironic: they blindfold the Son of God and demand prophecy from the one who has just prophesied his own glorification and their judgment (v.62). The guards strike the one who could have struck them down; the one who stilled the storm submits to their fists. Isaiah 50:6 — &#8220;I offered my back to those who beat me, my cheeks to those who pulled out my beard&#8221; — is fulfilled.</p>",
    "66": "<p>A servant girl of the high priest confronts Peter — the contrast of settings continues: above, Jesus speaks the most exalted Christological truth; below, Peter denies knowing him to a servant girl. The weakness of the human instrument is exposed: the one who swore to die with Jesus cannot maintain his identity before a minor household servant.</p>",
    "67": "<p>&#8220;You also were with that Nazarene, Jesus&#8221; — the servant girl identifies Peter by his association with Jesus. &#8220;With him&#8221; is the discipleship vocabulary (3:14 — &#8220;that they might be with him&#8221;); to be &#8220;with Jesus&#8221; is the definition of discipleship. Peter&#8217;s denial is the denial of his own identity: he is not merely denying knowing Jesus, he is denying being Jesus&#8217;s disciple.</p>",
    "68": "<p>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know or understand what you&#8217;re talking about&#8221; — the first denial. The irony is total: Peter, who confessed &#8220;You are the Christ&#8221; (8:29), now professes ignorance of Jesus. The one who was named Peter (rock) crumbles before a servant girl. The gap between the glory of Caesarea Philippi and the shame of the high priest&#8217;s courtyard is the gap that the resurrection will bridge.</p>",
    "69": "<p>The servant girl persists — she identifies Peter again to those standing nearby. Peter&#8217;s denial has not convinced her; the truth of his identity (being &#8220;with Jesus&#8221;) presses through his protests. The persistence of the testimony against him mirrors the persistence of false testimony against Jesus above; the patterns of the trial and the denial are deliberate parallels.</p>",
    "70": "<p>&#8220;Again he denied it&#8221; — the second denial. The &#8220;those standing near&#8221; note Peter&#8217;s Galilean accent as confirming identification with Jesus. Peter&#8217;s very voice marks him as one who belongs to the community of the Galilean teacher. He cannot erase the identity he has formed in three years of discipleship; the denial is a lie not only about Jesus but about himself.</p>",
    "71": "<p>&#8220;He began to call down curses, and swore, &#8216;I don&#8217;t know this man you&#8217;re talking about&#8217;&#8221; — the third denial with curses and oaths. The oath-taking escalates the lie from embarrassed denial to solemn renunciation; Peter invokes a curse on himself if he is lying, not knowing that the one he is cursing is the one who will absorb all curses for him (Gal 3:13 — &#8220;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&#8221;). The extreme of Peter&#8217;s failure is met by the extreme of Christ&#8217;s grace.</p>",
    "72": "<p>The second crowing of the rooster fulfills Jesus&#8217;s prediction exactly (v.30 — &#8220;before the rooster crows twice&#8221;). Peter remembers the word Jesus had spoken and &#8220;broke down and wept&#8221; — the memory of Jesus&#8217;s word is the mechanism of repentance: the word that predicted the failure also pointed beyond it (v.28 — &#8220;after I have risen, I will go ahead of you&#8221;). The weeping of Peter is the weeping of repentance; it is the beginning of the return that the risen Jesus will complete (John 21:15-19).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH14)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Mark mkt-christ: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
